Before we start with JavaScript Promises, we first have to know what JavaScript is and why we use promises in JavaScript.
So let’s first know JavaScript
JavaScript is a programming language built to make webpages more interactive — like updating content without reloading the page, animating elements, or responding to clicks.
JavaScript is running in two ways nowadays:

• In the browser (client-side) — every website you visit that reacts to your actions is running JavaScript.

• On servers (via Node.js) — the same language now powers backend APIs, which is probably where you use it most, given your background — means behind the scenes.
It’s dynamically typed, interpreted, and single-threaded, meaning it runs one operation at a time on one main thread. That last part is exactly why promises exist.
Now the question is — why promises?
JavaScript is single-threaded, but a lot of what it does — fetching data from an API, reading a file, querying a database — takes time and shouldn’t block everything else from running while it waits. If JS just stopped and waited for a slow network request, your entire app (or in Node’s case, your entire server) would freeze until it finished.
So JavaScript handles slow operations asynchronously: it kicks off the operation, keeps running other code, and gets notified later when the result is ready. Promises are the tool for managing that “notified later” part.
A promise is an object representing a value that doesn’t exist yet but will — or will fail trying. It has three states:

• Pending — still waiting (e.g. the API call hasn’t returned)

• Fulfilled — completed successfully, value is available

• Rejected — something went wrong, error is available
Let’s understand it using the example below.
For example, imagine you are going to a restaurant for dinner. To get food, first you have to order it — so when you order and get a message like “Yes, your order is being handled,” that is a promise.
Let’s understand it deeply.
1. Order ticket = a Promise
You sit down, tell the waiter what you want, and they hand you a ticket number. At this moment, one of three things is true:

• Your food is still being cooked → pending

• Your food is ready and being served → fulfilled

• The kitchen is out of that ingredient → rejected
That ticket is exactly what a JavaScript Promise is: a placeholder for a result you don’t have yet, but will or won’t eventually get.
const order = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
const kitchenHasIngredients = true; if (kitchenHasIngredients) {
resolve("Butter chicken, ready to serve");
} else {
reject(new Error("Out of chicken tonight"));
}
});
The waiter (the Promise constructor) doesn't cook the food themselves — they hand the ticket to the kitchen (the executor function) and walk away to serve other tables. That's the whole point: the restaurant keeps running while your food cooks. Nobody stands frozen at your table staring into the kitchen. That's asynchronous behavior.
2. Getting notified after food is ready — .then() or .catch()
You don’t sit and watch the kitchen. You tell the waiter: “when it’s ready, bring it to my table. If you can’t make it, let me know.”
order
.then(dish => console.log(`Served: ${dish}`))
.catch(error => console.log(`Sorry: ${error.message}`));.then() is your instruction for the happy path — meaning your food is ready.
.catch() is your instruction for when the kitchen can't deliver — meaning either there aren't proper ingredients for the recipe you want, or the dish doesn't exist.
You define both before the food is ready — that’s the beginner-level habit worth locking in early: promises are about describing what happens next, not about waiting around.
3. A multi-course meal — chaining promises
Now say you ordered a three-course meal: soup, then main course, then dessert. Each course only starts once the previous one is cleared from the table.
orderSoup()
.then(soup => {
console.log(`Enjoyed: ${soup}`);
return orderMainCourse();
})
.then(main => {
console.log(`Enjoyed: ${main}`);
return orderDessert();
})
.then(dessert => console.log(`Enjoyed: ${dessert}`))
.catch(error => console.log(`Meal interrupted: ${error.message}`));And this is chaining. Each .then() returns a new promise, so the next course only fires once the current one resolves. Notice there's only one .catch() at the end. If the kitchen messes up the soup, the whole rest of the meal gets skipped and you jump straight to that single catch — you don't need a try/catch at every course. That's the real advantage over old-school callback-based ordering, where you'd have had a waiter physically running back and forth for every single course, nesting deeper and deeper.
4. Ordering for the whole table — Promise.all()
You’re at dinner with five friends. Everyone orders separately, but nobody wants to eat until all the dishes are on the table at once.
Promise.all([
orderDish("pasta"),
orderDish("pizza"),
orderDish("salad"),
orderDish("soup"),
orderDish("steak"),
])
.then(dishes => console.log("Everyone's food is here:", dishes))
.catch(error => console.log("One dish failed, holding the whole table:", error.message));Promise.all() waits for every promise to resolve before moving on.
But — here’s the catch (literally): if even one dish fails, the entire table’s order fails. One kitchen mistake on the steak, and nobody at the table gets served, even the friends whose pasta and pizza were perfectly fine. HAHAHA.
This models real backend scenarios well — like fetching a user’s profile, their orders, and their payment info all together before rendering a dashboard. If any one of those three calls fails, you often don’t want to show a half-broken page.
5. When you don’t want one bad dish to ruin your whole menu or dinner — Promise.allSettled()
Sometimes you want to know about every dish — whether it’s available or not, its taste, and its reviews.
Promise.allSettled([
orderDish("pasta"),
orderDish("unavailable-fish"),
orderDish("salad"),
]).then(results => {
results.forEach(result => {
if (result.status === "fulfilled") {
console.log(`Served: ${result.value}`);
} else {
console.log(`Couldn't serve: ${result.reason.message}`);
}
});
});allSettled here works as a waiter who comes back and gives you a full status report — two dishes made it and one didn't — instead of throwing their hands up over a single failure.
Useful when partial success is still useful, like sending notifications to five users where one bad email address shouldn’t block the other four.
6. Whoever gets their order first — Promise.race()
For example, if you order the same dish from two different restaurants/apps at once, just to see which one comes first — whichever arrives first, you accept it and eat it. You don’t care about the other order.
Promise.race([
orderFromApp("SwiftEats"),
orderFromApp("QuickBite"),
]).then(dish => console.log(`First to arrive: ${dish}`));Promise.race() settles as soon as any one of the promises settles — win or lose.
This maps directly onto real patterns like timeouts: race your actual API call against a “give up after 5 seconds” promise, and whichever resolves first wins.
const timeout = new Promise((_, reject) =>
setTimeout(() => reject(new Error("Kitchen too slow, order cancelled")), 5000)
);Promise.race([fetchOrderStatus(), timeout])
.then(status => console.log(status))
.catch(error => console.log(error.message));
7. Talking like a normal person, not like a robot — async/await
Everything above is real, working promise syntax. But once you’re fluent, constantly writing .then().then().catch() starts to feel like a machine at the entrance of a restaurant, reading a menu word by word.
Regulars just talk normally. async/await is that normal voice — same promises underneath, cleaner sentence structure on top.
async function haveDinner() {
try {
const soup = await orderSoup();
console.log(`Enjoyed: ${soup}`); const main = await orderMainCourse();
console.log(`Enjoyed: ${main}`);
const dessert = await orderDessert();
console.log(`Enjoyed: ${dessert}`);
} catch (error) {
console.log(`Meal interrupted: ${error.message}`);
}
}
await pauses that function (not the whole restaurant, not the whole app) until the promise settles, then hands you the result directly — no .then() needed. It reads top to bottom like a normal sequence of events, while still being fully non-blocking under the hood.
I hope this clears up how promises work.
In short
A promise is a ticket for a result you don’t have yet. You attach instructions for success (.then) and failure (.catch) instead of waiting around.

• Chain them for steps that depend on each other.

• Use Promise.all when every dish matters and one failure should hold the whole order.

• Use Promise.allSettled when partial success is still useful.

• Use Promise.race when you only care about whichever finishes first.
And once you know all the things, then return to your modern era and use async/await to write promises in a cleaner way.
